<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-172-502  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 172 502.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Fall 1989 v2 n4 p58(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Viruses demand prosecution.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Herger, Wally.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many computer viruses that have come to light lately highlight ageneral trend away from ethical behavior that may be a sideproduct of the rapid growth of public access to computers.andP;  Thenature of computer viruses, which can stay hidden in a system forlong periods of time, make it difficult to apprehend computercriminals.andP;  Once apprehended, the task of prosecuting suchindividuals is made even more difficult because current computerlaws do not adequately address the subject of computer viruses.andO;Additionally, uniformity needs to be established among thenation's computer laws.andP;  Legislation alone will not solve thecomputer crime problem.andP;  Safe computing practices and an effort toeducate computer users in the field of computer ethics, startingwith the youngest users, are also needed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer CrimeComputer VirusesLegislationEthics.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>